==Early life== Mori was born in 1971 in [[Nagoya]], Japan, and grew up in Japan, [[New Jersey]], USA, and London. When Mori was twelve, she moved to England.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} Her father was sent back to Japan when Mori was fifteen.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} She was then given the choice of either staying in London or moving back with her father.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} She chose to stay in England, partly because she wanted to finish her [[GCSE]]s and gain some qualifications.<ref>[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eVmDF2byBoI "The Wright Stuff - Naoko Mori and the papers"] YouTube video</ref>
Her father later opened a [[bank account]] for her, handed her a cheque book and told her to find a flat or a [[bed sit]] for herself to live in.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} Mori said that being on her own at such a young age helped her to be a very independent person, although it was still a scary world to be faced so young.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}
==Acting career== [[File:Naoko Mori.jpg|160px|thumb|left|Mori at [[Comic Con]] 2008.]] From 1993â1994, Mori had a regular role on the hospital drama ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' as the hospital receptionist Mie Nishikawa. Film roles followed, including appearances in ''[[Spice World (film)|Spiceworld: The Movie]]'' (1997) and ''[[Topsy-Turvy]]'' (1999), and a leading role in ''Running Time'' (2000).{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} Mori also appeared in the television programmes ''[[Judge John Deed]]'' (2001), ''[[Spooks]]'' (2002), ''[[Mile High]]'' (2003)<ref name="mile high1">{{cite web | title=Episode Guide | work=Mile High fansite | url=http://www.mile-high.co.uk/episodeguides.php?id=13 | accessdate=2007-08-01}}</ref> and ''[[Powers (TV series)|Powers]] (2004)''.<ref>[http://www.startrader.co.uk/Action%20TV/guide2000/powers.htm Action TV Online - Powers episode guide]</ref> In 1995, she had a small role as a Japanese computer hacker in the film ''[[Hackers (film)|Hackers]]''. Mori had a major role in the 2005 BBC docu-drama ''Hiroshima'', which contained dramatic re-enactments of the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|1945 atomic bombing]]. Mori also provided the [[voice acting]] for the villainess Mai Hem for the game ''[[Perfect Dark Zero]]''. She also played Mia, hostess of the short-lived game show ''Hot Tub Ranking'' the same year. The programme ran for 6 episodes.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}
Also in 2005, Mori had a small role as Dr Sato in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' episode "[[Aliens of London]]". Producer [[Russell T Davies]] took note of her performance and decided to bring the character back as a regular in the first two series of the ''Doctor Who'' spin-off ''[[Torchwood]]''.<ref name="torchwood1">{{cite web | title=Torchwood's latest members | work=BBC Press Office | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2006/04_april/24/torchwood.shtml | accessdate=2006-04-24}}.</ref> Mori's ''Torchwood'' character, [[Toshiko Sato]], was killed in ''[[Exit Wounds (Torchwood)|Exit Wounds]]'', the final episode of ''Torchwood''âs second series, but has not ruled out the possibility of returning to the show at a later date.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} She returned to the West End on November 20, 2006, when she took over the role of Christmas Eve from [[Ann Harada]] in the London production of ''[[Avenue Q]]'', a role which she played until 14 April 2007.<ref>{{cite web | title=Avenue Q preview review | url=http://www.nowt2do.co.uk/review.php?id=89 | accessdate=2006-10-20}}</ref> Mori portrayed [[Yoko Ono]] in the BBC Four production ''Lennon Naked'', which aired in the UK on Wednesday 23 June 2010.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/2010/wk25/wed.shtml#wed_lennon "FATHERHOOD SEASON - Lennon Naked"] 23 June 2010, BBC</ref> The film reunited her with [[Christopher Eccleston]], who played [[John Lennon]], opposite whom she played Dr Sato in her ''Doctor Who'' appearance.
==Personal life== Mori is a [[Buddhism in Japan|Japanese Buddhist]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Carole |last=Gordon |title=Interview with Torchwood star Naoko Mori |url=http://www.eclipsemagazine.com/channel/hollywood_insider/interview_with_torchwood_star_naoko_mori |work=Eclipse Magazine |date=2007-01-01 |accessdate=2007-01-03 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070106022351/http://www.eclipsemagazine.com/channel/hollywood_insider/interview_with_torchwood_star_naoko_mori |archivedate = January 6, 2007}}</ref> She wanted to become a singer before she was an actress.<ref name="daemonstv.com">[http://www.daemonstv.com/2008/04/19/interview-naoko-mori-torchwood-part-one/ "Interview: NAOKO MORI from TORCHWOOD (Part One)"] at Daemon's TV web site</ref>
